covered: Valid Request: Scenarios cover successful retrieval with various parameter combinations (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05).
Empty Response: Tests for no results (TC06, TC24) and empty arrays when pagination exceeds data (TC07, TC08).
Query Parameters: Extensive coverage of valid/invalid combinations (TC01–TC05, TC08–TC12, TC18, TC27).
Pagination: Tests for offset/limit behavior (TC02, TC07, TC08, TC05, TC26) and edge cases (TC07, TC08, TC26).
Authorization: Tests for missing and invalid tokens (TC13, TC14) and standard auth flow (Background).
Error Handling: Various 4xx/5xx scenarios including invalid input, invalid audit, service outage, system error (TC09, TC12, TC15, TC16).
Reliability/Resilience: Performance and concurrency scenarios (TC19, TC20).
Data Integrity/Audit: Tests for FULL/MINIMAL audit details (TC03, TC04, TC05).
Data volume and compatibility: Large data and backward compatibility scenarios (TC19, TC21, TC23).
Edge/robustness: Extra unexpected query parameters (TC18), partially populated database (TC23).
Partial input: Search with partial input (TC27).
gaps: Caching Behavior: No tests verify caching headers (ETag/Cache-Control) or related caching behavior.
Rate Limiting: No explicit tests for rate limiting or throttling under burst conditions.
Explicit 4xx mapping verification: While many 4xx are covered, explicit verification of 403 vs 401 and exact error payload structure is not uniformly asserted across all scenarios.
UI accessibility test (TC22) may be optional if no UI client exists; ensure alignment with project reality.
recommendations: Add tests for caching headers presence and correctness (ETag, Cache-Control) to confirm caching behavior.
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests to validate behavior under high request load.
Clarify and extend assertions on error payload shapes for 4xx/5xx responses to ensure consistency (e.g., specific error codes/messages).
If UI exists, keep accessibility tests; otherwise document rationale and consider API accessibility implications.
